# Git Workflow

## Branch Strategy

- `main` — production branch. Only receives merges from `development` when a release is ready.
- `development` — integration branch. All feature branches merge here.
- Feature branches — created from `development` for every new feature, fix, or task.

### Branch Naming

```
feature/<short-description>    # new features
fix/<short-description>        # bug fixes
chore/<short-description>      # maintenance, deps, config
refactor/<short-description>   # refactoring without behavior change
```

### Workflow

1. Always branch off `development` for new work.
2. Keep feature branches short-lived — merge back quickly.
3. Never commit directly to `main` or `development`.
4. After merging to `development`, delete the feature branch.

## Commit Conventions

Use conventional commits. Keep messages concise and meaningful.

```
feat: add user profile page
fix: prevent duplicate socket connections on reconnect
chore: update axios to 1.7
refactor: simplify board store actions
test: add e2e for login flow
```

### Rules

- One logical change per commit — don't bundle unrelated changes.
- Write the **why**, not the what (the diff shows the what).
- No WIP commits on shared branches. Squash or amend locally before pushing.
- Stage intentionally — review `git diff --staged` before committing.
- Never commit `.env`, secrets, `node_modules`, or build artifacts.
- Do not put editor or AI tool attribution in commit messages (e.g. no "made with Cursor", "Co-authored-by: bot", or similar unless the project explicitly requires it).
